ISTANBUL, TURKEY — Two women armed with guns opened fire at the U.S. consulate in northern Istanbul on Monday, only a day after the U.S. deployed F-16 fighter jets to a Turkish airbase to support the country\'s fight against ISIS. A witness told Reuters that one of the women fired four to five rounds at several security officials and consulate officers.

One of the female attackers tried to run to a nearby residential building where police officers pursuing her shot at her several times. A local resident who witnessed the shooting told Turkey’s Anadolu Agency that the police asked the woman to surrender but she refused and replied, “I will never surrender to you.” Turkish police eventually shot and injured the woman and they arrested her.

The apprehended woman is reportedly a member of the Revolutionary People’s Liberation Army-Front, a far-left Marxist-Leninist party in Turkey. Police are still searching for her accomplice.

Turkey has been on high alert against attacks from the Islamic State and Kurdish forces after the country recently started launching separate airstrikes against both groups.

